@mclovin9091
Sounds like you just copied the file from the .iso file. If you download Virtual Clone drive (or any other disk image loader) you load the .iso file into it as if you had put the actual DVD into a disk drive. Then you can install the game from there. (another alternative would be to download something like ImgBurn and create an install disk from the .iso file) It should be able to tell if you have a 32bit or 64 bit system all on it's own if you do this correctly.

I suggest deleting anything you copied over. 

When you do the install, make sure you click "cancel" when it asks you for the CD key. After it is done installing, browse the CD (virtual or physical, whichever route you decide to go) and copy the files from the "CRACK" folder into where your game installed. I usually just rename the original files so that if I ever need them they are still there, but you can just copy over them if you want.

